<%= faq_schema([
  { question: "How do I calculate HVAC duct size?", answer: "Divide the required airflow (CFM) by the target velocity (fpm) to get the duct's required cross-sectional area in square feet. For a round duct, diameter = 2 × √(area / π). For a rectangular duct with a chosen aspect ratio, short side = √(area / aspect) and long side = short × aspect. Multiply square feet by 144 to get square inches." },
  { question: "What is a good velocity for residential ducts?", answer: "ACCA Manual D recommends 700-900 fpm for supply trunks, 600-700 fpm for supply branches, and 500-700 fpm for return trunks. Lower velocity gives quieter operation and less static pressure loss but requires larger ducts. Higher velocity lets you use smaller ducts but causes whoosh noise, turbulence, and more fan power." },
  { question: "What is equivalent round diameter?", answer: "Rectangular ducts have more friction per unit airflow than round ducts of the same area because their corners create turbulence. The ASHRAE equivalent round formula (De = 1.30 × (ab)^0.625 / (a+b)^0.25) gives the round diameter with the same friction loss as a given rectangular duct. Use this to look up friction from round-duct design tables." },
  { question: "Is round or rectangular better?", answer: "Round ducts are more efficient (less friction per CFM), easier to seal, and often cheaper per foot. Rectangular ducts fit better in tight ceiling and wall cavities. Pro tip: use round whenever you can fit it, and switch to rectangular only where depth is restricted (between joists, above soffits, etc.)." },
  { question: "How much does aspect ratio matter?", answer: "Aspect ratios up to 3:1 add only 10-15% friction compared to round. At 4:1 the penalty climbs to 25-40%. Beyond 4:1 (very flat ducts) friction escalates and air distribution gets uneven. Keep residential rectangular ducts at 2:1 when possible, 3:1 if constrained, and avoid 4:1+ unless you really have no other option." }
]) %>

